# Module 4: Storage & File Management

# Topic 25: Mount Points ⭐⭐⭐⭐

## Concept

A **Mount Point** is a connection between **external cloud storage** (S3, ADLS, GCS) and **DBFS**.

> **Simple definition:** A Mount Point is like creating a shortcut from DBFS to your cloud storage.

---

## Why do we need Mount Points?

Suppose your company stores data in AWS S3.

Without a Mount Point, every notebook has to use the full S3 path:

```text
s3://company-data/sales/orders.csv
```

Instead, create a Mount Point:

```text
/mnt/sales
```

Now everyone can simply use:

```text
/mnt/sales/orders.csv
```

This makes code simpler and reusable.

---

## Theory

A Mount Point does **not** copy data into Databricks.

It only creates a **reference (link)** to external cloud storage.

Think of it like a Windows shortcut:

```text
Desktop Shortcut
        │
        ▼
Actual Folder
```

Deleting the shortcut **does not delete** the original folder.

Similarly,

```text
Mount Point
      │
      ▼
AWS S3 / ADLS / GCS
```

The data remains in cloud storage.

---

## Architecture

```text
Notebook
    │
    ▼
DBFS Mount Point (/mnt/sales)
    │
    ▼
Cloud Storage
(S3 / ADLS / GCS)
    │
    ▼
orders.csv
```

---

## Path Structure

Mounted path:

```text
/mnt/sales/orders.csv
```

Cloud path:

```text
s3://company-data/orders.csv
```

Both point to the **same file**.

---

## Syntax

### Mount Storage

```python
dbutils.fs.mount(
    source="s3://company-data",
    mount_point="/mnt/sales"
)
```

### Read File

```python
df = spark.read.csv("/mnt/sales/orders.csv")
```

### List Files

```python
display(dbutils.fs.ls("/mnt/sales"))
```

### Unmount

```python
dbutils.fs.unmount("/mnt/sales")
```

---

## Real Example

Suppose your company has:

```text
AWS S3

company-data
     │
orders.csv
customers.csv
products.csv
```

Instead of every notebook using:

```text
s3://company-data/orders.csv
```

The admin creates:

```text
/mnt/company-data
```

Now every Data Engineer reads:

```python
spark.read.csv("/mnt/company-data/orders.csv")
```

The code is cleaner and easier to maintain.

